  author: Gwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: "The rites between master and disciple are of utmost importance. The sages compared the master to both sovereign and parent, establishing that reverence should be uniform—thus cultivating noble virtue and enriching human relations. In the age of the Three Dynasties and before, the Way of the Master shone most brightly, and so governance flourished and customs were refined. When the Han established the examination system, the master-disciple rites persisted, though gradually transformed. By the Tang, these observances flourished greatly: those who administered the examinations were called \"seat-masters,\" and those selected were called \"disciples.\" Yet the master-disciple rites dwelled merely in this distinction.\n\nIn our Eastern Kingdom, since the reign of King Gwangjong of Goryeo, these observances have been most elaborate. Examination administrators would prepare lavish feasts, don official robes, lead their disciples, and receive their former masters with celebration in their homes—treating them as they would their own parents. The royal court would order the preparation of banquet halls and bestow court music as marks of honor. Thus the seat-master regarded disciples as his own sons, and disciples regarded their master as their father. Such was the depth of respect between them.\n\nFor long ages under stable rule, the realm pursued learning and culture above all, yet extravagance grew unchecked and costs multiplied endlessly, sometimes requiring provincial levies that took months to fulfill. In the year of Gihyu under King Gongmin's reign, seeking to reform these excesses, the court adopted the examination procedures of China and prohibited the feasting ceremonies.\n\nIn the year Gapín, Lord Yi of Gwangyang, serving as Minister of State Affairs, presided over the examinations. Our present Minister Zhao Jun of Pyongyang, through imperial decree, achieved highest honors. His reputation spread daily as he wielded the pen of imperial edicts in the Hall of Worthies, upheld the law in the Censorate, and as Chief of Punishments saw corruption fade and as Inspector of the South saw piracy cease. All hoped for his greater advancement.\n\nIn the year Mujeong, when our present Sovereign was great general, he returned victorious from quelling rebellion and appointed Lord Zhao to head the Censorate. With utmost dedication to duty, the Minister left no task undone: he abolished private holdings to restore fair boundaries, strengthened the code of laws to subdue wrongdoing, and established the Gongyang King to restore the Wang clan's sacrifices. All the realm, within and without, looked with hope toward his wisdom.\n\nIn the summer of Gyeongohwanyear, as Minister of State Affairs overseeing the examinations, we find the elderly Lord Yi—who had served as Chamberlain and reached nearly eighty winters—yet unbent and vigorous, his pure virtue and steadfast integrity a model for all officials, his discernment keen and his ability to recognize talent unmatched, his blessings abundant and his years prolonged. All revered him.\n\nIn the autumn of Imsinnyear, when Gongyang lost the Way and met his downfall, Lord Zhao, as Vice-Premier, championed righteousness, set forth the plan, and elevated the new sovereign, thereby establishing a foundation enduring as stone for ten thousand generations. His merit was paramount in founding the new dynasty, and his rank elevated to Minister. Though his honor reached its height, he served Lord Yi with unfailing deference, observing the courtesy of a filial son with redoubled care.\n\nLord Yi, leading his disciples, invited Lord Zhao to a celebration at his home and composed a verse to congratulate him on his appointment as Minister. Fellow disciples and literary worthies of the court added their own poems to this grand scroll.\n\nThe following summer, Lord Zhao again presided over the examinations—unprecedented for one of his rank to hold the examining seat twice. Since the examination system began, this has never occurred.\n\nSong In, a fellow examination candidate, came to me saying: \"Poems require prefaces; this is ancient custom. Here especially, we must record such virtue. You should compose the opening words.\" \n\nI reflect thus: The Zhaos of Pyongyang have accumulated generations of benevolence and virtue. Councilor Jeong-suk served King Chungnyeol with distinguished accomplishment, his house standing foremost among officials. Through the ages they have maintained this excellence, reaching unto the present.\n\nOur Lord, possessing the talents of Yi Yin and Lü Shang, has illumined the Six Classics and penetrated the histories through the learning of Zhou and Cheng. His vast capacity serves the people, his righteous reputation stabilizes society. His authority manifests in the Censorate, his virtue befits the office of the Chief Counselor. He has upheld his family's honor, supported the royal enterprise, and will leave a legacy bright as any in history. His noble deeds deserve inscription on bronze and bamboo, transmitted for ten thousand ages—what need of poets' words?\n\nYet without the odes of Qi'ao, we would not know the literary virtue of Duke Mu of Wei; without the Great Brightness hymn, we could not perceive the martial brilliance of Lü Shang. Thus poetry's importance cannot be dismissed. Lord Zhao's founding merit is recorded in our national histories; his reverence toward his master deserves commemoration in the verses of worthy men.\n\nIn serving his master with utmost depth of respect, and in guiding his own disciples through this same reverence, Lord Zhao demonstrates that when such respect extends to all humanity, human relations become profound and customs beautiful. His disciples, being likewise men of talent and virtue, will surely in time serve him as he has served his master—this is beyond doubt.\n\nAh! When the rites of mastery are honored, the Way of the Master shines once more. When the Way of the Master is bright, the foundations of education are strengthened. When customs are refined and society virtuous, highest governance is achieved—and this springs from this very source. Even the splendor of the Three Dynasties might thus be restored. No work of statesmanship surpasses this. Therefore do I gladly write this preface."
  footnotes:
    - The 'seat-master' (座主) refers to the chief examiner, while 'disciples' (門生) were successful examination candidates. A special honor-relationship developed between them in East Asian societies.
    - Yi Yin and Lü Shang were legendary sage-ministers of antiquity, exemplars of wisdom and virtue in statecraft.
    - The 'Way of the Master' (師道) refers to the proper observance of respect and hierarchical relationships in education, considered fundamental to moral cultivation and social order.
    - The Three Dynasties (夏商周) represent the legendary golden age of governance in Chinese civilization.
